const ARTICLES={};
ARTICLES['jpg-vs-png-vs-webp']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-jpg-vs-png-vs-webp.html',title:'JPG vs PNG vs WebP: Which Image Format Should You Use in 2026?',date:'June 2026',read:'5 min',cat:'Image Tools',excerpt:'Choosing between JPG, PNG and WebP affects your website speed, quality and SEO. Here is the definitive guide.',html:'<h2>The quick answer</h2>\n<p>Use <strong>WebP</strong> for all web images — it is smaller than JPG and PNG with no visible quality loss. Use <strong>JPG</strong> for photographs you share via email or print. Use <strong>PNG</strong> only when you need a transparent background.</p>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>Convert your existing images to WebP in seconds using the free <a href="#/t/jpg-to-webp">JPG to WebP</a> or <a href="#/t/png-to-webp">PNG to WebP</a> converter.</p></div>\n<h2>JPG (JPEG) — best for photographs</h2>\n<p>JPG uses lossy compression, which means it discards some image data to reduce file size. It is ideal for photographs and images with gradients because compression artifacts are less noticeable in complex scenes.</p>\n<ul><li>Smallest file size for photographs</li><li>No transparency support</li><li>Quality degrades slightly each time you save</li><li>Best for: social media posts, blog hero images, product photography</li></ul>\n<h2>PNG — best for graphics with transparency</h2>\n<p>PNG uses lossless compression — no quality is lost when saving. But file sizes are significantly larger than JPG. PNG supports transparent backgrounds, making it the standard for logos, icons and UI elements.</p>\n<ul><li>Supports transparency (alpha channel)</li><li>Lossless — perfect quality every time</li><li>Larger file sizes than JPG</li><li>Best for: logos, screenshots, icons, images with text</li></ul>\n<h2>WebP — the modern standard</h2>\n<p>Google developed WebP in 2010 and all major browsers now support it. WebP files are typically 25-35% smaller than JPG and 26% smaller than PNG at equivalent quality. It supports both lossy and lossless modes, plus transparency.</p>\n<ul><li>25-35% smaller than JPG at the same quality</li><li>Supports transparency like PNG</li><li>Supported by Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge</li><li>Best for: everything on the web</li></ul>\n<h2>Quick comparison</h2>\n<p><strong>File size:</strong> WebP &lt; JPG &lt; PNG (for photos) | PNG &lt; WebP (for graphics with transparency)</p>\n<p><strong>Transparency:</strong> WebP ✓ | PNG ✓ | JPG ✗</p>\n<p><strong>Best for web:</strong> WebP wins in almost every case.</p>\n<a href="#/t/jpg-to-webp" class="tool-cta-link">Convert JPG to WebP Free →</a>\n<a href="#/t/png-to-webp" class="tool-cta-link">Convert PNG to WebP Free →</a>\n<h2>When NOT to use WebP</h2>\n<p>WebP is not ideal when sharing files with people who may open them in old software. Some older image editing tools and email clients do not support WebP. In those cases, JPG or PNG remains the safer choice.</p>\n<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Does converting JPG to WebP reduce quality?</summary><p>Slightly, because JPG is already lossy and converting adds another compression step. Use the highest quality setting (85-90%) to minimise quality loss. The file size savings usually outweigh this minor reduction.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Can I use WebP for emails?</summary><p>Not reliably. Gmail supports WebP but Outlook does not. For email images, use JPG for photographs and PNG for logos.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Which format is best for SEO?</summary><p>WebP. Smaller images load faster, and Google uses page speed as a ranking factor. Google Search Console and PageSpeed Insights both recommend using WebP.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['compress-images-without-losing-quality']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-compress-images-without-losing-quality.html',title:'How to Compress Images Without Losing Quality',date:'June 2026',read:'4 min',cat:'Image Tools',excerpt:'Reduce image file sizes by 60-80% without any visible quality loss using the right tools and settings.',html:'<h2>Why image compression matters</h2>\n<p>Large images are the single biggest cause of slow websites. A page that takes 4 seconds to load loses 25% of its visitors before they see anything. Compressing your images can cut page weight by 60-80% with no visible difference to the human eye.</p>\n<a href="#/t/image-compressor" class="tool-cta-link">Compress Images Free →</a>\n<h2>Lossy vs lossless compression</h2>\n<p><strong>Lossy compression</strong> permanently removes image data. At quality 80-85%, the results are visually identical to the original but 60-70% smaller. This is the right choice for web images.</p>\n<p><strong>Lossless compression</strong> removes metadata and optimises encoding without losing a single pixel. File sizes reduce by 20-30%. Use this for images that need to remain pixel-perfect, such as product screenshots or medical imagery.</p>\n<h2>The best settings for web images</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>JPG quality 80-85%</strong> — visually identical to 100%, typically 60% smaller</li><li><strong>WebP quality 80%</strong> — smaller still than JPG 85%, excellent browser support</li><li><strong>PNG</strong> — use lossless compression only; lossy PNG looks noticeably degraded</li></ul>\n<h2>How to compress in bulk</h2>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/image-compressor">TARUMAK Image Compressor</a> lets you drag in multiple images at once and download them all compressed. It runs in your browser — your images never leave your device.</p>\n<h2>Convert to WebP for maximum savings</h2>\n<p>If you convert JPG or PNG images to WebP before compressing, you get an additional 25-35% reduction in file size. Use the <a href="#/t/jpg-to-webp">JPG to WebP converter</a> and then apply compression.</p>\n<h2>Remove EXIF data too</h2>\n<p>Photos taken on a smartphone contain hidden EXIF metadata — GPS coordinates, camera model, shutter speed. This can add 50-100KB to an image. Use the <a href="#/t/exif-remover">EXIF Data Remover</a> to strip it out, which also protects your privacy.</p>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What quality setting should I use?</summary><p>Start at 80% and compare with the original. If you cannot spot the difference, use 80%. If you can, try 85%. Going above 90% gives almost no visual benefit but significantly increases file size.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Should I compress PNG files?</summary><p>Only with lossless compression. Lossy PNG compression causes visible colour banding on flat-colour images like logos and screenshots. Convert PNG to WebP instead for the best size-to-quality ratio.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['merge-pdf-online-free']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-merge-pdf-online-free.html',title:'How to Merge PDF Files Online — Free and Instant',date:'June 2026',read:'3 min',cat:'PDF Tools',excerpt:'Combine multiple PDF files into one document in seconds — no software, no sign-up, completely free.',html:'<h2>Merge PDFs without installing software</h2>\n<p>You do not need Adobe Acrobat or any paid software to merge PDF files. The <a href="#/t/pdf-merger">TARUMAK PDF Merger</a> combines multiple PDFs in your browser — your files are never uploaded to a server.</p>\n<a href="#/t/pdf-merger" class="tool-cta-link">Merge PDFs Free →</a>\n<h2>Step-by-step guide</h2>\n<ol><li>Open the <a href="#/t/pdf-merger">PDF Merger tool</a></li><li>Drag and drop your PDF files into the upload area (or click to browse)</li><li>Drag the file cards to reorder them if needed</li><li>Click "Merge PDFs"</li><li>Download your combined PDF</li></ol>\n<h2>How to reorder pages before merging</h2>\n<p>If you need to rearrange individual pages — not just files — use the <a href="#/t/pdf-organizer">PDF Organizer</a> instead. It shows thumbnail previews of every page and lets you drag them into any order before exporting.</p>\n<h2>Is it safe to merge PDFs online?</h2>\n<p>With TARUMAK Tools, yes. All processing happens locally in your browser using JavaScript. Your PDF files are never sent to our servers, never stored, and never seen by anyone else. You can even use it offline after the page has loaded.</p>\n<h2>When merging does not work</h2>\n<p>If a PDF is password protected, you need to unlock it first. Use the <a href="#/t/pdf-unlock">PDF Unlock Tool</a> to remove the password, then merge.</p>\n<h2>Related PDF tools</h2>\n<div class="art-tools"><a href="#/t/pdf-splitter">Split PDF</a><a href="#/t/pdf-organizer">Reorder Pages</a><a href="#/t/pdf-compressor">Compress PDF</a><a href="#/t/pdf-page-remover">Remove Pages</a></div>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Is there a file size limit?</summary><p>No artificial limits. The practical limit depends on your browser and available RAM. Most modern computers can handle PDFs up to a few hundred MB without issues.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Can I merge more than two PDFs?</summary><p>Yes — drag in as many files as you need. There is no limit on the number of PDFs you can combine.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['social-media-image-sizes-2026']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-social-media-image-sizes-2026.html',title:'Social Media Image Sizes 2026 — Complete Cheatsheet',date:'June 2026',read:'4 min',cat:'Marketing Designer',excerpt:'Every social media image size for Instagram, Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, YouTube and Pinterest — updated for 2026.',html:'<h2>Why image sizes matter</h2>\n<p>Each platform has its own optimal image dimensions. Use the wrong size and your image gets cropped awkwardly, appears blurry, or gets stretched — all of which look unprofessional. The <a href="#/t/social-image-resizer">Social Media Image Resizer</a> handles all platforms automatically.</p>\n<a href="#/t/social-image-resizer" class="tool-cta-link">Resize Images for Social Media →</a>\n<h2>Instagram image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Square Post:</strong> 1080 × 1080 px (1:1)</li><li><strong>Portrait Post:</strong> 1080 × 1350 px (4:5) — gets more screen real estate</li><li><strong>Landscape Post:</strong> 1080 × 566 px (1.91:1)</li><li><strong>Story / Reel:</strong> 1080 × 1920 px (9:16)</li><li><strong>Profile Picture:</strong> 320 × 320 px (displays at 110px)</li></ul>\n<h2>Facebook image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Post Image:</strong> 1200 × 630 px</li><li><strong>Cover Photo:</strong> 820 × 312 px</li><li><strong>Story:</strong> 1080 × 1920 px</li><li><strong>Profile Picture:</strong> 170 × 170 px</li></ul>\n<h2>Twitter / X image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Post Image:</strong> 1200 × 675 px (16:9)</li><li><strong>Header / Banner:</strong> 1500 × 500 px</li><li><strong>Profile Picture:</strong> 400 × 400 px (displays as circle)</li></ul>\n<h2>LinkedIn image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Post Image:</strong> 1200 × 628 px</li><li><strong>Personal Banner:</strong> 1584 × 396 px</li><li><strong>Company Logo:</strong> 300 × 300 px</li><li><strong>Company Banner:</strong> 1128 × 191 px</li></ul>\n<h2>YouTube image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Thumbnail:</strong> 1280 × 720 px (16:9) — minimum 640px wide</li><li><strong>Channel Art:</strong> 2560 × 1440 px</li><li><strong>Profile Picture:</strong> 800 × 800 px</li></ul>\n<h2>Pinterest image sizes 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Standard Pin:</strong> 1000 × 1500 px (2:3) — performs best</li><li><strong>Square Pin:</strong> 1000 × 1000 px</li><li><strong>Story Pin:</strong> 1080 × 1920 px</li></ul>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>Resize any image to any of these sizes instantly with the free <a href="#/t/social-image-resizer">Social Media Image Resizer</a>. Just upload, pick a platform, drag to crop, and download.</p></div>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What resolution should social media images be?</summary><p>Always export at 72 DPI for digital use — higher DPI does not improve quality on screens and only increases file size. The pixel dimensions listed above are what matters.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What file format should I use for social media?</summary><p>JPG for photographs (smaller file size). PNG for graphics with text or transparency. Most platforms convert images anyway, so quality difference is minimal.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['utm-link-builder-guide']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-utm-link-builder-guide.html',title:'UTM Links Explained: How to Build and Track Campaign URLs',date:'June 2026',read:'5 min',cat:'Marketing Designer',excerpt:'UTM parameters tell Google Analytics exactly where your traffic comes from. Learn to build them in 60 seconds.',html:'<h2>What is a UTM link?</h2>\n<p>A UTM link is a regular URL with extra parameters added to the end that tell Google Analytics where a visitor came from. Without UTM links, GA4 shows traffic as "Direct" when the source is actually a newsletter, a social post, or a paid ad.</p>\n<a href="#/t/utm-builder" class="tool-cta-link">Build UTM Links Free →</a>\n<h2>The five UTM parameters</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>utm_source</strong> — Where the traffic comes from (google, newsletter, instagram)</li><li><strong>utm_medium</strong> — The marketing channel (cpc, email, social, organic)</li><li><strong>utm_campaign</strong> — The campaign name (summer_sale, product_launch)</li><li><strong>utm_term</strong> — The paid keyword, for Google Ads (optional)</li><li><strong>utm_content</strong> — Used for A/B testing different versions (header_link, footer_cta)</li></ul>\n<h2>Example UTM URL</h2>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>https://tarumak.com?<span style="color:var(--p1)">utm_source=newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=june_tools</span></p></div>\n<p>This tells GA4: "This visitor came from our June newsletter, via email, as part of the june_tools campaign."</p>\n<h2>Best practices</h2>\n<ul><li>Use lowercase only — utm_source=Google and utm_source=google are counted separately in GA4</li><li>Use hyphens instead of spaces: june-launch not june launch</li><li>Be consistent with your naming — create a spreadsheet of standard values</li><li>Always track paid ads, emails, and social posts</li><li>Do not add UTM parameters to internal links — it breaks session tracking</li></ul>\n<h2>Where to see UTM data in GA4</h2>\n<p>In Google Analytics 4, go to Reports → Acquisition → Traffic Acquisition. You will see sessions broken down by source, medium and campaign. Click into any row to see the full UTM data.</p>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Do UTM links affect SEO?</summary><p>No. Google ignores UTM parameters for indexing purposes. They are only read by analytics tools.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What is the difference between source and medium?</summary><p>Source is the specific place (google, facebook, mailchimp). Medium is the channel type (cpc, social, email). Think of medium as the category and source as the specific platform within that category.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Do UTM links work with Google Analytics 4?</summary><p>Yes. GA4 reads all standard UTM parameters and attributes sessions accordingly. You can view them under Acquisition reports.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['what-is-open-graph-image']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-what-is-open-graph-image.html',title:'Open Graph Images: What They Are and How to Create One',date:'June 2026',read:'4 min',cat:'Marketing Designer',excerpt:'OG images are the preview images that appear when you share a link on social media. Here is how to make one that gets clicked.',html:'<h2>What is an Open Graph image?</h2>\n<p>An Open Graph (OG) image is the preview image that appears when you share a web page link on Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, WhatsApp or iMessage. Without one, platforms use a random image from the page — often a logo or an irrelevant photo. A good OG image dramatically increases click-through rates.</p>\n<a href="#/t/og-image-gen" class="tool-cta-link">Create OG Image Free →</a>\n<h2>The correct OG image size</h2>\n<p>The standard OG image size is <strong>1200 × 630 px</strong> at 72 DPI. This ratio (1.91:1) works across all major platforms. Using a different size results in cropping or borders around the image.</p>\n<h2>How to add OG image to your website</h2>\n<p>Add this to the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> of your HTML:</p>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>&lt;meta property="og:image" content="https://yoursite.com/og-image.png" /&gt;<br>&lt;meta property="og:title" content="Page Title" /&gt;<br>&lt;meta property="og:description" content="Page description" /&gt;</p></div>\n<h2>What makes a good OG image?</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Clear headline text</strong> — readable even as a small thumbnail</li><li><strong>Brand colors</strong> — consistent with your site design</li><li><strong>Logo or brand name</strong> — so people recognise the source instantly</li><li><strong>No clutter</strong> — one message, one image, one CTA</li><li><strong>High contrast</strong> — text must be readable on all backgrounds</li></ul>\n<h2>Test your OG image</h2>\n<p>After adding the meta tag, use the Facebook Sharing Debugger or Twitter Card Validator to see exactly how your link preview will appear. These tools also let you force a cache refresh if you have updated the image.</p>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Why is my OG image not showing on social media?</summary><p>Most likely a caching issue. Facebook and LinkedIn cache OG data aggressively. Use the platform debugger tools to force a refresh. Also make sure the image URL is absolute (starts with https://) not relative.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Can I use the same OG image for every page?</summary><p>Technically yes, but it reduces engagement. Unique OG images per post or page perform significantly better, especially on LinkedIn and Twitter.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['best-free-pdf-tools-2026']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-best-free-pdf-tools-2026.html',title:'Best Free PDF Tools in 2026 (All Browser-Based, No Sign-Up)',date:'June 2026',read:'5 min',cat:'PDF Tools',excerpt:'A curated list of the best free PDF tools available in 2026 — merge, split, compress, edit and more without installing software.',html:'<h2>Why use browser-based PDF tools?</h2>\n<p>Installing desktop software for occasional PDF tasks is inefficient. Browser-based tools let you merge, split or compress PDFs in seconds with no downloads, no sign-up and no subscription. TARUMAK Tools offers 15 free PDF tools that run entirely in your browser.</p>\n<h2>Best tools for each task</h2>\n<h3>Merge PDFs</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-merger">PDF Merger</a> combines multiple PDFs into one. Drag and drop files, reorder them, and download the merged document in seconds. Handles dozens of files at once.</p>\n<h3>Split or extract pages</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-splitter">PDF Splitter</a> lets you extract specific pages or ranges ("1-3, 7, 10-12") into separate PDFs, or split every page into individual files.</p>\n<h3>Compress PDFs</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-compressor">PDF Compressor</a> rasterises each page at reduced quality to shrink file size. Best for PDFs that contain large images — text-heavy PDFs compress less.</p>\n<h3>Visually reorder pages</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-organizer">PDF Organizer</a> shows thumbnail previews of every page. Drag them into any order, rotate individual pages, and download the reorganised document.</p>\n<h3>Convert PDF to JPG</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-to-jpg">PDF to JPG converter</a> renders each PDF page as a separate JPG image — perfect for sharing individual pages or creating image previews.</p>\n<h3>Extract text from PDF</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-to-text">PDF to Text converter</a> extracts all text content from a PDF and saves it as a plain .txt file — useful for copying content from scanned or locked PDFs.</p>\n<h3>Password protect PDF</h3>\n<p>The <a href="#/t/pdf-password-protect">PDF Password Protector</a> encrypts a PDF with a password before you share it. Recipients need the password to open the file.</p>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>All 15 TARUMAK PDF tools are completely free, run in your browser, and never upload your files to a server.</p></div>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Are browser-based PDF tools safe?</summary><p>With TARUMAK Tools, yes. All processing happens locally using JavaScript libraries (pdf-lib and PDF.js). Your files are never sent to any server.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Do these tools work on mobile?</summary><p>Yes — all tools are mobile-responsive. You can merge, compress and convert PDFs directly from an iPhone or Android device.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['create-pdf-lead-magnet']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-create-pdf-lead-magnet.html',title:'How to Create a PDF Lead Magnet That Grows Your Email List',date:'June 2026',read:'6 min',cat:'Marketing Designer',excerpt:'A lead magnet is a free resource you offer in exchange for an email address. Here is how to create one in under 10 minutes.',html:'<h2>What makes a great lead magnet?</h2>\n<p>A lead magnet that converts has three qualities: it solves a specific problem, it delivers value immediately, and it is easy to consume in under 10 minutes. A 200-page ebook is not a lead magnet — a one-page checklist is.</p>\n<a href="#/t/pdf-lead-magnet" class="tool-cta-link">Create Your Lead Magnet Free →</a>\n<h2>The 4 best lead magnet formats</h2>\n<h3>1. Checklist</h3>\n<p>The highest-converting format. Specific, actionable, scannable. Example: "Website Launch Checklist: 27 Things to Do Before Going Live."</p>\n<h3>2. Cheatsheet</h3>\n<p>A condensed reference guide. Example: "Social Media Image Sizes 2026 — All Platforms in One Sheet." People bookmark these and return repeatedly.</p>\n<h3>3. Step-by-step guide</h3>\n<p>Walks the reader through a process from start to finish. Example: "How to Set Up Google Analytics 4 in 15 Minutes." Numbered steps build confidence.</p>\n<h3>4. Resource list</h3>\n<p>A curated collection of tools, links or templates. Example: "The 12 Free Design Tools Every Freelancer Needs." Easy to create, extremely shareable.</p>\n<h2>What to write in your lead magnet</h2>\n<ul><li>Solve one very specific problem — not a general topic</li><li>Use plain language — no jargon or academic writing</li><li>Include your brand name, URL and a next step (visit your site, follow on social)</li><li>Keep it to one page for checklists and cheatsheets; 3-5 pages maximum for guides</li></ul>\n<h2>Create it in 10 minutes</h2>\n<p>Use the <a href="#/t/pdf-lead-magnet">PDF Lead Magnet Creator</a> to generate a branded PDF in your choice of template. Enter your title, items, brand name and accent color — the tool generates a professionally-formatted PDF instantly.</p>\n<h2>Where to promote it</h2>\n<ul><li>Your website homepage — above the fold, in a popup or sticky bar</li><li>Blog posts related to the topic — inline CTA after every article</li><li>Social media bio link (Instagram, Twitter, LinkedIn)</li><li>Pinterest boards related to your niche</li></ul>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What tool should I use to send emails to subscribers?</summary><p>ConvertKit is excellent for creators and designers — free up to 1,000 subscribers with automation included. Mailchimp is also popular and has a generous free plan.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>How many subscribers can I expect from a lead magnet?</summary><p>A well-targeted lead magnet with decent traffic converts at 20-40% of landing page visitors. 100 visitors per day = 20-40 new subscribers per day with a strong offer.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['best-favicon-size']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-best-favicon-size.html',title:'Favicon Size Guide: What Size Should Your Favicon Be in 2026?',date:'June 2026',read:'3 min',cat:'Developer Tools',excerpt:'The complete guide to favicon sizes — what dimensions you need, which formats to use, and how to generate them all at once.',html:'<h2>What is a favicon?</h2>\n<p>A favicon is the small icon that appears in the browser tab, bookmarks bar and search results next to your website name. A missing or low-resolution favicon makes a site look unfinished and untrustworthy.</p>\n<a href="#/t/favicon-generator" class="tool-cta-link">Generate Favicons Free →</a>\n<h2>Required favicon sizes in 2026</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>16 × 16 px</strong> — browser tab (desktop)</li><li><strong>32 × 32 px</strong> — browser tab (high DPI), Windows taskbar</li><li><strong>48 × 48 px</strong> — Windows site shortcuts</li><li><strong>64 × 64 px</strong> — high-DPI displays</li><li><strong>180 × 180 px</strong> — Apple Touch Icon (iPhone home screen)</li><li><strong>192 × 192 px</strong> — Android Chrome home screen</li><li><strong>512 × 512 px</strong> — PWA splash screen, Google search</li></ul>\n<h2>Which format to use</h2>\n<p>Create your favicon in <strong>PNG format</strong> for all sizes. The legacy .ico file (which packs 16px and 32px into one file) is still supported by some older browsers and can be included for maximum compatibility. The <a href="#/t/favicon-generator">TARUMAK Favicon Generator</a> creates all sizes from your original image.</p>\n<h2>How to add your favicon</h2>\n<div class="art-callout"><p>&lt;link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="32x32" href="/favicon-32x32.png"&gt;<br>&lt;link rel="apple-touch-icon" sizes="180x180" href="/apple-touch-icon.png"&gt;<br>&lt;link rel="icon" type="image/x-icon" href="/favicon.ico"&gt;</p></div>\n<h2>Favicon design tips</h2>\n<ul><li>Use a simple shape — detail is lost at 16px</li><li>Avoid text unless it is a single letter or two characters</li><li>Use high contrast between the icon and background</li><li>Test at actual size (16px) before finalising</li></ul>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Can I use a JPG as a favicon?</summary><p>JPG is supported by most browsers but PNG is preferred because it supports transparency — so the favicon looks good on any browser tab background color.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Why is my new favicon not showing up?</summary><p>Browsers aggressively cache favicons. Do a hard refresh (Ctrl+Shift+R or Cmd+Shift+R) or clear your browser cache. It can take several hours for all visitors to see the new favicon.</p></details>\n'};
ARTICLES['brand-color-extraction-guide']={url:'https://tarumakstudio.com/article-brand-color-extraction-guide.html',title:'How to Extract Brand Colors from Any Logo or Image',date:'June 2026',read:'4 min',cat:'Marketing Designer',excerpt:'Extract your exact brand colors as HEX, RGB and CSS variables from any image in seconds — no design software needed.',html:'<h2>Why brand color consistency matters</h2>\n<p>Consistent use of brand colors builds recognition. Studies show that consistent brand presentation across all channels increases revenue by up to 23%. But to stay consistent, you need your exact HEX codes — not an approximation from memory.</p>\n<a href="#/t/brand-color-extract" class="tool-cta-link">Extract Brand Colors Free →</a>\n<h2>How to extract colors from a logo</h2>\n<ol><li>Open the <a href="#/t/brand-color-extract">Brand Color Extractor</a></li><li>Upload your logo (PNG with transparent background works best)</li><li>The tool automatically identifies the dominant colors</li><li>Click any color to copy its HEX code</li><li>Download the full palette as CSS variables or a PNG reference</li></ol>\n<h2>What format do you need?</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>HEX (#6366f1)</strong> — for web/CSS and most design tools</li><li><strong>RGB (99, 102, 241)</strong> — for screen-based design and some web frameworks</li><li><strong>HSL (239°, 84%, 67%)</strong> — for CSS custom properties and color manipulation</li><li><strong>CSS Variables</strong> — paste directly into your stylesheet</li></ul>\n<h2>Generating a full palette from a brand color</h2>\n<p>Once you have your primary brand color, use the <a href="#/t/color-palette-gen">Color Palette Generator</a> to create a complete design system. It generates complementary, analogous and triadic palettes from any base color — useful for creating consistent UI color systems.</p>\n<h2>Using extracted colors in your workflow</h2>\n<ul><li>Add them to a Figma styles library for the whole team</li><li>Save as CSS custom properties in your design system</li><li>Add to your brand guidelines document</li><li>Use in ad creatives for social media to maintain consistency</li></ul>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>What if the tool extracts the wrong colors?</summary><p>Upload a PNG with a transparent background rather than a white background — this prevents the white background from being detected as a brand color. The cleaner the logo, the more accurate the extraction.</p></details>\n<details class="art-faq"><summary>Can I extract colors from a website screenshot?</summary><p>Yes — take a screenshot of the website, save it as PNG, and upload it to the Brand Color Extractor. The tool will identify the most prominent colors on the page.</p></details>\n'};

